songs.full_title: 18 by 5 Seconds of Summer

description.plain:
“18” is the fifth track on 5 Seconds Of Summer’s self-titled debut. It’s a bouncy track about the troubles of age and dating someone who’s older. It was also the first track on their live album LIVESOS.

Billboard thought positively of it, with editor Jason Lipshutz saying:

The entire appeal of 5 Seconds of Summer’s style is on display on “18,” a legitimately funny, insanely catchy ode to the frustration of waiting for adulthood when you’re still a punk kid. The guys effortlessly sell lines like “She’s got a naughty tattoo/In a place that I want to get to/But my mom still drives me to school,” bouncing along with the Ashton Irwin’s snappy percussion and sounding like they’re having a blast with the concept.

songs.full_title: 2011 by 5 Seconds of Summer

description.plain:
On “2011” 5 Seconds of Summer looks back at the beginning of their career after ten successful years together.

The band announced the song via their socials on November 30, 2021, as a celebration for the group’s ten year anniversary:

This Friday, we’re releasing a new song called “2011,” just for you. We wrote “2011” to celebrate 10 years of this band, 10 years of adventures through life, and most of all, 10 years of you, our fans. We love you, and we can’t wait for the next 10. Out everywhere December 3rd.

Drummer Ashton Irwin has also posted a drum teaser of “2011” months before the song’s release.

songs.full_title: Amnesia by 5 Seconds of Summer
songs.title: Amnesia

description.plain:
“Amnesia” is 5 Seconds Of Summer’s 2014 release that rocketed to the top of the charts not long after they debuted it on tour. It was included on their eponymous debut album 5 Seconds Of Summer.

The song’s release was accompanied by a somber black-and-white lyric video, a  change of pace for the normally high-flying band.

The song was written by a small army of people, including the two brothers from Good Charlotte and one of the dudes from Color Me Badd.



In this song, the narrative voice reminisces about his past relationship and the pain of hearing the fact that his ex has ‘moved on’ – he doesn’t want to believe that she is happy with someone else that is not him.

songs.full_title: Broken Home by 5 Seconds of Summer
songs.title: Broken Home

description.plain:
“Broken Home” is a power ballad about the emotional impact a disintegrating marriage has on a couple’s teen daughter.

It’s the 12th track on the deluxe version of  5 Seconds of Summer’s 2015 album Sounds Good Feels Good.

The song was co-written with Joel and Benji Madden of Good Charlotte.



In an interview with Fuse, producer John Feldmann revealed that the song’s theme caused some debate about the song’s authenticity.

Other than Ashton, the three guys have parents who are still together. Ashton has never met his father. Ashton really connected into the theme. “We’re saying something with this song, it’s going to connect with the audience, at least 50% of our audience come from broken homes. We’re actually taking a stand.” The other guys are loyal and family-driven and sweet, so they were like, “What are our parents going to think about us singing about a broken home when we don’t come from broken homes? How authentic is it?” It was a two-month debate.

“Close as Strangers” is a bonus track from the Target exclusive version of the band’s debut album, 5 Seconds of Summer.

This song is about one or more of them missing their partner while on tour. This is a theme the band has tackled throughout the discography, in songs such as “Wherever You Are” and “Beside You”. The band members hail from Sydeney, Australia, and had to deal with leaving loved ones behind when they catapulted to fame and toured internationally – eventually moving to England.

songs.title: COMPLETE MESS

description.plain:
“COMPLETE MESS” follows 5 Seconds of Summer’s anniversary single “2011” and is the lead single of their fifth studio album 5SOS, released on September 23rd 2022.

An informal announcement of the song was made on February 18th 2022, when the band sent a magazine to a fan and retweeted a tweet she made about the song’s title and release date. However, the official announcement was made via Instagram post a week later, on February 25th, alongside the official cover art of the song.

5 Seconds of Summer have been teasing the song for a while before its release. The first two snippets were via 5SOS' TikTok, on February 19th and February 20th. A few days later, they started posting the snippets on their Twitter. The first ones, on February 25th, 26th, 27th and 28th, were all instrumental. On March 1st, a day before the song’s release, the band posted the last snippet, that revealed part of the lyrics for “COMPLETE MESS”.

songs.full_title: Don't Stop by 5 Seconds of Summer
songs.title: Don’t Stop

description.plain:
“Don’t Stop” was released as the second single from 5 Seconds Of Summer’s eponymous debut album.

Despite being their only song to miss the top forty in the US (it reached #46), it performed successfully in other countries, reaching #2 in the UK and topping the charts in Ireland, New Zealand, Scotland, and Ukraine. It also reached #3 in Australia.

This uptempo track is a bright, punk-influenced rock song and draws influence from bands such as The Cars and Green Day.

The band stated:

“Don’t Stop” is like the party song – it’s something you can dance to or turn up loud in your car. It’s basically about the girl that everyone wants at a party.

Check out the video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MKfzMOC19Fc
